  </div>
</header>

<div class="greek-key"></div>

<div class="page-body">

  <!-- TABLE OF CONTENTS -->
  <div class="toc">
    <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
    <ul class="toc-list">
      <li><a href="#how-to-use">How to Use This Guide</a></li>
      <li><a href="#official-instruments">Official Instrument Referrals</a></li>
      <li><a href="#intake-context">Reading Intake Context Fields</a></li>
      <li><a href="#part-a">Part A — Career Charting</a></li>
      <li><a href="#session-a1">Session 1 — Work Values + Holland</a></li>
      <li><a href="#session-a2">Session 2 — DISC + VIA</a></li>
      <li><a href="#part-b">Part B — Education Path Planner</a></li>
      <li><a href="#session-b1">Session 1 — Holland RIASEC</a></li>
      <li><a href="#session-b2">Session 2 — VARK + VIA</a></li>
      <li><a href="#session-b3">Session 3 — Academic Interests + Practical Priorities</a></li>
      <li><a href="#part-c">Part C — Combined Profile</a></li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- HOW TO USE -->
  <section id="how-to-use" class="how-to-use">
    <span class="part-label">Reference</span>
    <h2 style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:1.6rem;color:#fff;margin-bottom:20px;">How to Use This Guide</h2>
    <p>Each framework section follows the same five-step pattern. Use it consistently across every section in every session.</p>
    <table class="ref-table" style="margin-top:20px;">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Step</th>
          <th>What to Do</th>
          <th>Why It Matters</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong style="color:var(--amber-light);">1. Orient</strong></td><td>Briefly explain what the framework measures and why it matters.</td><td>Gives context before results — prevents misinterpretation.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong style="color:var(--amber-light);">2. Present</strong></td><td>State the result clearly. Read the description. Then pause.</td><td>Silence after presenting gives the client space to react authentically.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong style="color:var(--amber-light);">3. Validate</strong></td><td>Use the validation prompt before offering any interpretation.</td><td>The client's first reaction is often the most diagnostic data in the session.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong style="color:var(--amber-light);">4. Probe</strong></td><td>Use the coaching prompts to deepen the conversation.</td><td>Prompts move the session from data review to genuine self-discovery.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong style="color:var(--amber-light);">5. Connect</strong></td><td>Link this result to others across frameworks.</td><td>Cross-framework convergence is the strongest signal in the entire assessment.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <div class="coach-note">
      <strong>Coach Note:</strong> The most valuable moment in any debrief is when a client says "That's exactly right" or "That's not me at all." Both reactions are equally useful. Build around confirmations. Investigate disagreements.
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- OFFICIAL INSTRUMENTS -->
  <section id="official-instruments">
    <span class="part-label">Reference</span>
    <h2 style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:1.6rem;color:#fff;margin-bottom:20px;">Official Instrument Referrals</h2>
    <p>Both assessments direct clients to full official versions on the results page. Reinforce these referrals in the debrief.</p>
    <table class="ref-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Framework</th><th>Official Assessment</th><th>Access</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Work Values (DOL)</td><td>CareerOneStop Work Values Matcher</td><td>careeronestop.org (free)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Holland RIASEC</td><td>Self-Directed Search (SDS) by PAR</td><td>self-directed-search.com</td></tr>
        <tr><td>DISC Profile</td><td>Everything DiSC by Wiley</td><td>discprofile.com</td></tr>
        <tr><td>VIA Character Strengths</td><td>VIA Survey by VIA Institute</td><td>viacharacter.org (free)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>VARK Learning Styles</td><td>Official VARK Questionnaire</td><td>vark-learn.com (free)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Career Data</td><td>O*NET OnLine</td><td>onetonline.org (free)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Program Data</td><td>College Scorecard</td><td>collegescorecard.ed.gov (free)</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <div class="section-divider"></div>

  <!-- INTAKE CONTEXT -->
  <section id="intake-context">
    <span class="part-label">Reference</span>
    <h2 style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:1.6rem;color:#fff;margin-bottom:20px;">Reading Intake Context Fields</h2>
    <p>Both assessments capture several unscored intake fields that appear verbatim on the results page. These qualitative responses are often more diagnostic than any scored section.</p>
    <table class="ref-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Intake Field</th><th>What It Reveals</th><th>How to Use in Debrief</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Career Transition Stage</td><td>Where the client is in their career arc.</td><td>Calibrates ambition level. New entrants need different guidance than mid-career changers.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Peak Professional Experience</td><td>When and why they felt most alive at work.</td><td>Read their words back verbatim. Identify which frameworks their peak story confirms or contradicts.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Barriers &amp; Motivators</td><td>What has held them back and what would excite them.</td><td>Most actionable coaching conversation. Return to these explicitly in every session.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Work Environment Preferences</td><td>Concrete working conditions they need.</td><td>Filter career direction suggestions.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Career Destination Vision (Edu)</td><td>Where the student imagines themselves at 30.</td><td>The gut-check for every program recommendation.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Exploration Readiness (Edu)</td><td>Whether the student is genuinely open or under pressure.</td><td>Shapes the entire coaching posture.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Academic Self-Efficacy (Edu)</td><td>How confident the student is academically.</td><td>Low: prioritize accessible programs. High: do not undersell options based on GPA alone.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Support System &amp; Expectations (Edu)</td><td>Who else is influencing this decision.</td><td>Surfaces external pressure.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <!-- PART A -->
  <div class="part-header" id="part-a">
    <span class="part-label">Part A</span>
    <h2>Career Charting Debrief Guide</h2>
    <p>The Career Charting assessment spans 2 sessions across 4 frameworks: Work Values Inventory, Holland RIASEC, DISC, and VIA. Total question count: 70.</p>
    <div class="part-meta">
      <span>2 Sessions</span>
      <span>4 Frameworks</span>
      <span>70 Questions</span>
    </div>
    <table class="ref-table" style="margin-top:24px;">
      <thead><tr><th>Session</th><th>Frameworks</th><th>Questions</th><th>Focus</th><th>Approx. Length</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>1</td><td>Work Values + Holland</td><td>38</td><td>Who are you and what environments fit you?</td><td>60–90 min assessment + 30–45 min debrief</td></tr>
        <tr><td>2</td><td>DISC + VIA</td><td>32</td><td>How do you operate and what drives you?</td><td>30–45 min assessment + 45–60 min debrief</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <div class="coach-note" style="margin-top:16px;">
      <strong>Coach Note:</strong> Session 2 carries the heavier debrief load. VIA benefits most from extended conversation — character strengths are harder to self-identify than behavioral style. The Barriers and Motivators intake fields should be revisited explicitly in Session 2.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- SESSION A1 -->
  <div class="session-header" id="session-a1">
    <span class="session-label">Part A — Session 1</span>
    <h3>Work Values Inventory &amp; Holland RIASEC</h3>
  </div>

  <p>Begin Session 1 debrief after the client completes both Work Values and Holland sections. These two frameworks together answer the foundational career question: What environments fit this person, and what do they most need from work to feel satisfied?</p>
  <div class="quote-block">"Last session we gathered the data. Today we look at what it means together — and more importantly, what you think it means. I'll share each result and I want your honest reaction before I interpret anything."</div>

  <!-- Framework 1: Work Values -->
  <div class="framework">
    <span class="framework-number">Framework 1</span>
    <h4>Work Values Inventory (DOL)</h4>

    <div class="block">
      <span class="block-label">Framework Purpose</span>
      <p>Identifies which of six occupational value domains are most important to the client: Achievement, Independence, Recognition, Relationships, Support, and Working Conditions. Work value alignment is one of the strongest long-term predictors of career satisfaction and retention.</p>
