  <!-- PART C -->
  <div class="part-header" id="part-c">
    <span class="part-label">Part C</span>
    <h2>Combined Profile Report — Debrief Guide</h2>
    <p>The Combined Profile Report is generated when a client has completed both the Career Charting and Education Path Planner assessments. It is accessed from the results page of either tool when a matching session is found in the database.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="coach-note">
    <strong>Combined Note:</strong> Do not share the Combined Profile Report with clients before the debrief conversation. The document is most valuable as a live coaching tool — the conversation it generates is more important than the document itself.
  </div>

  <div class="block" style="margin-top:32px;">
    <span class="block-label">What the Report Shows</span>
    <table class="ref-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Section</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Side-by-side Holland codes</td><td>Identifies whether career environment fit and academic field interest point in the same direction.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>VIA convergence across both tools</td><td>Confirms whether character strength is consistent across career and education contexts.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>DISC style + VARK learning style</td><td>Shows how the client operates (DISC) and how they learn best (VARK).</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Top Work Value vs. Academic cluster</td><td>Cross-references the deepest career need with the academic interest direction.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Career Destination Anchoring</td><td>Displays the client's own vision for their career — the gut-check for all recommendations.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Three Combined Pathway Recommendations</td><td>Synthesizes all frameworks into actionable paths with confidence levels.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="block">
    <span class="block-label">Reading the Convergence Levels</span>
    <table class="ref-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>What It Means</th><th>How to Debrief</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong style="color:#4ade80;">High Confidence</strong><br><span style="font-size:0.78rem;color:var(--text-faint);">Holland + VIA align</span></td><td>Both assessments point in the same direction independently. Strongest possible signal.</td><td>Validate and move to action. Name the convergence explicitly.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong style="color:var(--amber-light);">Moderate Confidence</strong><br><span style="font-size:0.78rem;color:var(--text-faint);">partial alignment</span></td><td>One or two frameworks align, others diverge.</td><td>Identify which frameworks align and which diverge. Explore divergence before finalizing.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong style="color:#f87171;">Divergence Detected</strong><br><span style="font-size:0.78rem;color:var(--text-faint);">low alignment</span></td><td>Career and education profiles point in meaningfully different directions.</td><td>Most diagnostic finding in a combined profile. Explore whether external pressure is driving one side.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="block">
    <span class="block-label">Combined Debrief Prompts</span>

    <div style="margin-bottom:16px;">
      <span style="font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.16em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--amber);display:block;margin-bottom:6px;">Opening the Combined Session</span>
      <div class="quote-block">"We have now completed both assessments. Before I show you the combined picture, I want to ask you one question: if you had to choose between the career your scores suggest and the education direction your scores suggest — which one would you choose without hesitation?"</div>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-bottom:16px;">
      <span style="font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.16em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--amber);display:block;margin-bottom:6px;">When Holland Codes Align</span>
      <div class="quote-block">"Both your career and education assessments independently pointed toward [Holland type] environments. That level of consistency is significant — what does that tell you about what you've known for a long time that you maybe haven't admitted yet?"</div>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-bottom:16px;">
      <span style="font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.16em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--amber);display:block;margin-bottom:6px;">When Holland Codes Diverge</span>
      <div class="quote-block">"Your career interests point toward [Career Holland], but your academic interests point toward [Education Holland]. Before I interpret anything — which of those two feels more genuinely yours, and which might reflect what you thought you were supposed to want?"</div>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-bottom:16px;">
      <span style="font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.16em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--amber);display:block;margin-bottom:6px;">Values-Anchored Unified Direction</span>
      <div class="quote-block">"Regardless of where the other frameworks land — your top work value is [Value] and your signature strength is [VIA]. Every career and program recommendation I make is filtered through those two things. If any option doesn't honor both of them, it comes off the list. Does that feel right?"</div>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-bottom:16px;">
      <span style="font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.16em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--amber);display:block;margin-bottom:6px;">Career Destination Gut-Check</span>
      <div class="quote-block">"You described your ideal career as [Career Destination]. Looking at the combined recommendations — does this path actually lead there? If not — what would need to change?"</div>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-bottom:16px;">
      <span style="font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.16em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--amber);display:block;margin-bottom:6px;">VARK-to-Career Format Alignment</span>
      <div class="quote-block">"Your VARK result shows you learn best through [style]. That has implications beyond program selection — careers that require ongoing learning in a format that matches your style produce significantly higher long-term satisfaction. Does the career direction we're building toward actually involve learning that way?"</div>
    </div>
